pr_title: FLOE-578: removed ignored CSS properties
pr_body: Margin-top and height are ignored due to the display property. With 'display: inline', the width, height, margin-top, margin-bottom, and float properties have no effect. It makes no sense to set margin and height properties when the display has been set to inline.

', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 5, 29, 19, 32, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'sachin10101998', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 453723651, 'comment_body': "If using keyboard Tab key to navigate the post index, focus moves from the bottom of the page toward the top. This is a problem caused by the CSS transform rotation but the DOM order remaining the same. Ideally the DOM order should be consistent with Tab focus order so that people using only keyboards or switches (or other forms of navigation) don't get confused by focus moving backward. To fix this, I can see 2 ways: 1. When creating the Post collection, ensure the contents are sorted in reverse date order, or 2. In the loop traverse the collection in reverse so that the last collection item is first in the `ul` list. Option 1 is the preferred method as it keeps the logic for data handling in the controller, leaving the template to just render the contents. Option 2 is a bit of a hack and should only be used if Option 1 isn't possible for some reason. Side comment: `id` values should be unique in a document. The way `id` is being used here should really be a `class` instead. But if we use Option 1 or 2 above, we can get rid of these `id`s and remove the rotation CSS as it won't be needed anymore.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 13, 15, 13, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jhung', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 453746923, 'comment_body': "There's a strange bug here where part of the text content is appearing in a `

Are both needed?

Also, to be consistent with other IDRC web projects, I would like to propose that `eleventyport` be replaced with `start` (see below).

For example, in our web projects we have:
* `clean` - deletes node_modules and output / build directories.
* `build` - deletes any existing (old) output files, and generates the output.
* `install` - installs dependencies
* `start` - runs clean, build, then runs the server that watches for changes in the output

Examples:
* https://github.com/inclusive-design/idrc/blob/dev/package.json
* https://github.com/platform-coop-toolkit/pinecone/blob/dev/package.json

If you don't pin the versions, in general you'll need to use `npm ci` instead of `npm install` when installing dependencies. 

From what I understand the contrast is that pinning to specific versions you always get that versions. If you rely on the package-lock you'll get the latest considered release (based on how you've specified the version in the package.json file). This means that two people using the same code base may get different versions. In general that's likely going to be patch release versions. That's a benefit on one hand because it should just be bug fixes, but on the other hand any variation in codebase can make testing, debugging, and communicating issues more complicated. ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 2, 13, 33, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'jobara', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 435960703, 'comment_body': '```
